An analysis to predict future crimes from the hisorical crime data to stop them!

1. SCOPING

1.1. Aim

This project’s aim is to construct an accurate regression prediction model for crime occurence in New York City and thereby help the “Mayor’s Office of Criminal Justice” to strategize how to use its resources efficiently.The number of crimes(dependent variable) occuring in a census tract are predicted on the basis of independent variable information of census tract which is collected from ACS Data :

  1. race segregation
  2. population
  3. Unemployment rate
  4. number vacant units
  5. median household income
  6. Total population that has less than high school education percentage

1.2 Research Questions

What predictive methodologies can be adopted to predict crime?

2. DATA

2.1. Data Sources

The following data is collected from New York Police Department, Open Data and American Community Survey respectively : 1) NYPD’s Historic Complaint Data is colleted from https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Public-Safety/NYPD-Complaint-Data-Historic/qgea-i56i 2) NYC Boroughs from NYC Open data : https://data.cityofnewyork.us/City-Government/Borough-Boundaries/tqmj-j8zm 3) NYC Census Tracts from NYC Open Data : https://data.cityofnewyork.us/City-Government/2010-Census-Tracts/fxpq-c8ku 4) ACS(American Community Survey) Data for race distribution, population, population per acre, unemployment rates, vacant units, median household income, number of vacant units, total population that has less than high shool education percentage of census tracts.

2.2. Data Preparation

This section shows how the data was cleaned.

2.2.1 ACS Data Preparation

As there are only about 2160 census tracts in the city, some of the ACS data was processed in microsoft excel while historical crime data was processed in R Studio. Throughout the data cleaning process, some steps were taken to make a model that was more efficient. These are:

  1. Only census tracts with non-zero populations were considered
  2. The independent variables that had “NULL” entries were not considered to be a part of the final model.
  3. The Unemployment rate and less than high school education percentage data had “NA” entries in their columns. These were also not considered.

2.2.2 NYPD’s Historical Data Preparation

The historical crime data of NYPD is very large and has crime recordings from the year 2006 - 2017. From this, only 2010’s data and completed crimes were filtered for the prediction model. This is done so as the data was being joined with census tracts(whose boundaries were iterated decade wise) and also population counts were done decade wise which is one of the dependent variable in this model.

The crimes in the year were joined with census tract shapefile to visually understand where most crimes happened.

Finally, the independent variables were then joined to this as well.

The final section of this was also to divide the crime data as test(30%) data set and train(70%) data set. This is done so to estimate the performance of the model that was created.

3. Analysis

The most initial forms of predicting crimes was through GIS(Geographic Information system) Mapping. Experts were able to see patterns in crime occurences around the world. A 1998 study by Diana Ehlers and Gideon Pimstone used various factorsto predict crime rate per 100,000 in the United States. They concluded in their research that statistical methods such as regression analysis and correlation could be used to predict crime trends. Through them, policy makers can be given a “statistical glimpse of the future” (Ehlers, 1998).

Hence, I also tested various regression prediction models on the data that was collected to come up with the most accurate methology. The regression prediction models that were tested were based on the error values. Correlation and covariance were done to identify the factors on which the crime number per census tract was most dependent on. After that the following regression predictions were done :

  1. Linear regression models
  2. Multi-variant regression models
  3. Logistic regression 4)Random Forest
  4. XGBoost Prediction methodology

From the correlation analysis, we can see that the independent variables that have higher correlation with crime numbers per census tract are population, persons per acre, African-America population ,Hispanic population, Unemployment rate, vacant units number and less than high school education percentage. The variabls that do not correlate with the existing data are number of Whites per census tract, number of Asians per census tract, median household income of the census tract and total number of other race population per census tract.

The covariance indicated similar trends as that of correlation analysis:

Independent variables such as population, african-american population, Hispanic population, total number of houses, Number of houses occupied have a high covariance value and hence have very high impact on positive change in crime rate.

4. HAND OFF

4.1.Conclusions

From the analysis, there is a clear indication that the crime numbers within a census tract are dependent on population, persons per acre, African-American popultion, Hispanic populations, Unemployment rates and education levels. Although crimes are currently decreasing in NYC, the model indicates that the predicted values are more than the current values due to variations in the demographic data. Hence, it is important for “Mayor’s office of Criminal Justice” to invest the same or more in their policing services in the city.

Different types of predictions had different results. From the above regression models, we can see that XGBoost has the least error compared to the other methods for predicting crime. Hence, this is the best model for crime data for the year 2010. In this method, the implementation of the algorithm was engineered for efficiency of compute time and memory resources.The design goal was to make the best use of available resources to train the model. The two reasons to use XGBoost are also the two goals of this project : Execution speed and model performance.

According to Jason Brownlee, “this approach supports both regression and classification predictive modeling problems.”

Some of the other general recommendations include : policy makers should make strategies to make sure that racial clustering or segregation does not happen within census tracts. The vacant units can be minimised by changing its rent/cost of the unit upon the occupany. Non-populated census tracts have to invest in amenities, public places and entertainment buildings to attract population so that it get distributed as well.

4.2.Limitations

These analysis was done on only some demographic variables. Crime can be dependent on various other factors and for more accuracy, more variable should be incorporated into this model. The analysis could have been done for more years than just 2010 for better evaluation of the models.

4.3.Future Work/ Building upon the model

  1. Currently, the model is only for predicting number of crimes. This can be expanded to number of different types of crimes.
  2. This model can be automated for every 10 years to estimate crime numbers with changes in census tract boundaries. This will give estimates of crime numbers which can be used for distribution of resources and city planning.
